<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-234-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 234 234  OV: 08 233 876.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 12 1990 v7 n10 p77(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Peter Norton Computing Inc. Norton Disk Doctor. (Software Review)(one of eight evaluations of utility programs in 'Disk-diagnosticutilities find trouble spots.') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rosch, Winn L.; Dang, Lori J.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Peter Norton Computing Inc's Norton Disk Doctor, included in thecompany's $150 Norton Utilities general-purpose utility package,offers somewhat limited hard-disk diagnostic facilities.andP;  Itchecks the integrity of the disk boot record, active storageareas, and file-allocation table but performs only a cursory checkof disk sectors.andP;  It cannot find marginal clusters not flagged byDOS, and its read-only test is slow.andP;  Users say that NortonUtilities is well-documented and easy to use.andP;  Few users actuallyrequire a complex general purpose utility program.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Peter Norton Computing Inc. (products).andO;Product:   Norton Disk Doctor (Utility program).andO;Topic:     Utility ProgramsDiagnosticsEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Peter Norton Computing Inc.andM;NORTON DISK DOCTORandM;Norton Utilities, regarded as the epitome of disk-management software, has anew diagnostic program, Norton Disk Doctor, included in version 4.5.andM;As far as the diagnostic facilities of the $150 Utilities are concerned,however, a more appropriate name might be the Norton Disk Intern.andP;  Thisaspect of the otherwise excellent package is still in training.andM;Norton Disk Doctor examines several aspects of hard and floppy disks,checking the integrity of the boot record, the file-allocation table and theactive stoage areas.andP;  It can be driven from within the Norton Utilities mainmenu or from the command line.andM;According to its excellent documentation, Norton Disk Doctor can perform anexhaustive sector check of a disk, but in practice the good doctor gives thedisk a cursory look, at best.andP;  In testing, Norton Disk Doctor found nothingbut the cluster already flagged by DOS, skipping over the ailments found byread/write testing.andM;The disk M.D.andP;  is slow, too, spending 13 minutes and 46 seconds on theread-only test.andM;One menu choice in the Disk Doctor, Common Solutions, is unique andworthwhile.andP;  It offers three functions: making any disk bootable (moving datafrom the boot sectors if necessary); reviving a diskette (which puts a newphysical format on the floppy without altering its data contents); andrecovering from DOS&quot; RECOVER.COM (which sorts out the mess that running thatprocedure creates).andM;Peter Norton Computing Inc. can be reached in Santa Monica, Calif., at (213)319-2010.andM;Buyers say .andP;  .  .andM;&quot;You can't go wrong buying this product--it's easy to use andwell-documented,&quot; said Ken Moore, consultant at PC Help and Teaching, a PCconsulting firm in Aumsville, Ore.andP;  &quot;I've never had any problems orcomplaints about it from my clients.&quot;andM;According to Moore, less than half of all computer users need an extensivegeneral-purpose package such as this advanced version of Norton Utilities.andO;Still, he added, &quot;I wouldn't have a library without it.andP;  It's like havinginsurance.andP;  I hope that I never need to use it, but it's there if I do.&quot;andM;&quot;Some packages, such as Mace, have essentially the same functionality, butthey require more knowledge on the part of the end user to use themsuccessfully,&quot; said Paul Curtis, partner at Coast Computer Technology, anAnaheim, Calif., company specializing in data recovery.andP;  &quot;Norton can be usedby everybody, from the novice to the highly skilled technician.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>